WHO’s work is guided by the recommendations of theWHO World report on vision (2019)and the resolution on "Integrated, people-centred eye care, including preventable blindness and vision impairment" adopted at the Seventy-third World Health Assembly in 2020. The key strategy recommended in these documents is to make integrated people-centred eye care (IPEC) the care model of choice and to ensure its widespread implementation. It is expected that by shaping the global agenda on vision and eye care, the report and resolution will assist support efforts to reduce the burden of eye conditions and vision.
Some of WHO’s key areas of work and activities in the prevention of blindness include:
- working with Member States and other partners in the field to monitor theglobal targets for 2030on integrated people-centred eye care;
- supporting the integration of eye care in health systems through the implementation of a series of technical tools;
- supporting capacity-building of health workers who can provide care for the eyes;
- support countries to assess the provision of eye care services through the implementation of situation analysis tools;
- implementing SPECS 2030, an initiative to support countries in reaching the more than 800 million people in need of refractive error services;
- raising awareness on eye care through the development and provision of a range of materials and resources; and
- observing and promoting World Sight Day as an annual advocacy event.
